[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''Sir Robert Rich, 4th Baronet''' (3 July 1685 – 1 February 1768) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[cavalry]] officer. As a junior officer he fought at the [[Battle of Schellenberg]] and at the [[Battle of Blenheim]] during the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. He was then asked the raise a regiment to combat the threat from the [[Jacobite risings|Jacobite rising]] of 1715. He also served with the [[Pragmatic Sanction of 1713|Pragmatic Army]] under the [[John Dalrymple, 2nd Earl of Stair|Earl of Stair]] at the [[Battle of Dettingen]]  during the [[War of the Austrian Succession]]. As a [[Member of Parliament]] he represented three different constituencies but never attained political office.

==Career==
Born the son of [[Sir Robert Rich, 2nd Baronet]] and Mary Rich (née Rich, daughter of [[Rich baronets|Sir Charles Rich, 1st Baronet]]), Rich was [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the [[Grenadier Guards|1st Regiment of Foot Guards]] and [[lieutenant]] in the Army on 10 June 1700.<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/23496?docPos=5|title=Sir Robert Rich, 4th Baronet|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>

He fought in the [[War of the Spanish Succession]] at the [[Battle of Schellenberg]] in July 1704, where he was wounded, and at the [[Battle of Blenheim]] in August 1704, where he was wounded again.<ref name=heath245>Heathcote, p. 245</ref> Promoted to lieutenant in the [[South Wales Borderers|Brigadier-General Tatton's Regiment]] and [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in the Army, he succeeded his brother as 4th Baronet in October 1706, and was then promoted to captain in the 1st Regiment of Foot Guards and [[lieutenant-colonel]] in the Army in March 1708.<ref name=heath245/> In June 1708 he fought a [[duel]] with [[Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet, of Mildenhall|Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet]] who was wounded but survived.<ref name=heath245/>

When the threat of the [[Jacobite risings|Jacobite rising]] of 1715 became apparent Rich was asked to raise a regiment which subsequently became known as the [[17th Lancers|18th Dragoons]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=5349|supp=|startpage=1|date=23 July 1715|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>  That year he was also elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dunwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Dunwich]]. In June 1717 he was stripped of his regiment for voting against [[First Stanhope–Sunderland Ministry|the Government]] on a motion accusing [[William Cadogan, 1st Earl Cadogan|Lord Cadogan]] of fraud and embezzlement during the transport of some Dutch troops.<ref name=hop>{{HistoryofParliament|1715|first=Shirley|last=Matthews|title=RICH, Sir Robert, 4th Bt. (1685-1768), of Roos Hall, Suff. |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/rich-sir-robert-1685-1768}}</ref> He was defeated in the general election in 1722 but having strongly supported [[Robert Walpole|Sir Robert Walpole]], firstly when Walpole was in opposition and then when Walpole was in the [[Walpole–Townshend Ministry|Government]], was rewarded with the colonelcy of the [[13th Hussars]] in November 1722.<ref name=heath245/> 

He was elected as Member of Parliament for [[Bere Alston (UK Parliament constituency)|Bere Alston]] in February 1724 and became colonel of [[8th King's Royal Irish Hussars|Sir Robert Rich's Regiment of Dragoons]] in September 1725.<ref name=heath245/> In 1727 he changed constituency to become Member of Parliament for [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]] and was appointed a [[Groom of the Bedchamber]] to King George II, a position he held until 1759.<ref name=hop/>

Having been promoted to [[brigadier-general]] on 15 March 1727,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=6572|supp=| startpage=3|date=11 April 1727|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> he went on to be colonel of the [[Carabiniers (6th Dragoon Guards)|The King's Regiment of Carabineers]] in January 1731, colonel of the [[Horse Grenadier Guards|1st Troop Horse of Grenadier Guards]] in July 1733<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=7211|supp=|startpage=1|date=7 July 1733|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and, finally, colonel of the [[4th Queen's Own Hussars|4th Regiment of Dragoons]] in May 1735.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=7403|supp=|startpage=1|date=17 May 1735|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>

Promoted to [[major-general]] on 18 December 1735<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=7464|supp=|startpage=1|date=16 December 1735|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and [[lieutenant general]] on 17 July 1739,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=7823|supp=|startpage=1|date=14 July 1739|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Rich became [[Governor]] of the [[Royal Hospital Chelsea]] in May 1740.<ref name=chelsea>{{cite web|title=The Royal Hospital: Paymasters General and Officials, Survey of London: volume 11: Chelsea, part IV: The Royal Hospital |year=1927|pages= 37–60|url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=98501 |accessdate= 21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=7909|supp=|startpage=2|date=10 May 1740|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> He served with the [[Pragmatic Sanction of 1713|Pragmatic Army]] under the [[John Dalrymple, 2nd Earl of Stair|Earl of Stair]] at the [[Battle of Dettingen]] in June 1743 during the [[War of the Austrian Succession]].<ref name=heath245/> He also presided over a [[court martial]] of Lieutenant-General [[Thomas Fowke]], [[Governor of Gibraltar]], on a charge of disobeying orders in August 1756.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=9608|supp=|startpage=1|date=10 August 1756|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>

Rich was promoted to [[general]] of horse on 24 March 1746<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=8625|supp=|startpage=2|date=21 March 1746|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 3 December 1757.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=9744|supp=|startpage=1|date=29 November 1757|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In retirement he continued to live in the family home, [[Roos Hall]] in [[Beccles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Beccles, The History and Antiquities of the County of Suffolk: volume 1 |year=1846|pages= 1–35|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=75108 |accessdate= 21 July 2014}}</ref> He died on 1 February 1768.<ref name=heath246>Heathcote, p. 246</ref>
[[File:George II at Dettingen.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Rich fought under the [[John Dalrymple, 2nd Earl of Stair|Earl of Stair]] at the [[Battle of Dettingen]]]]

==Family==
In 1710 Rich married Elizabeth Griffith; they had three sons, including [[Sir Robert Rich, 5th Baronet]] and [[Rich baronets|Sir George Rich, 6th Baronet]], and one daughter, Elizabeth, who married [[George Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton]].<ref>Mosley, p. 838</ref>

